## 5. What implementing the rest would unlock

Ordered by likely value to OpenSC4:

1. **Network subfiles (§4.4)** — the city renders today with no roads, rails, power lines or
   pipes. `0xC9C05C6E` (3,335 ground-network tile records) plus the network index is the
   gateway to drawing the transport network, and the `CityView/ClassDefinitions/` graph
   classes are already waiting for it. This save is a good first target: no bridges, no
   tunnels.
2. **SimGrids (§4.5)** — the record header is fully decoded (this analysis parses all 136
   layers cleanly: own type id, dataId, resolution, dims at fixed offsets, 55-byte header).
   They power every data-view overlay (pollution, land value, crime, traffic…). A generic
   `SimGridSubfile` would be a small, high-leverage parser.
3. **Zone developer / item index (§4.8)** — per-tile zoning enables a zoning overlay and is
   needed before any simulation work.
4. **Region-view completeness** — use the localized LTEXT city name (`G=0x6AAEE931`) instead
   of the filename; decode the fields still marked unknown in `SC4ReadRegionalCity.gd`.
5. **Budget/ordinances/graphs (§4.6–4.7)** — only needed once simulation or UI panels exist.
6. **Terrain edge strips** (`0xA9DD6FF4` I=0x64–0x67) — four 129-float strips, almost
   certainly the neighbour-city edge altitudes used for cross-city edge matching.

